Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T4]: Conditional Access: Location-Based Access Control


Conditional access is a set of policies and configurations that control which devices have access to corporate services. After successful authentication, login attempts are evaluated against a predefined set of conditions to allow or block access. For example, attackers and APT groups usually target organizations in other countries, and it's not a big deal for defenders to create access policies based on geo-locations. 

 

From an email security perspective, a login attempt from a hostile country or country where your organization does not do business should be flagged and blocked. Security teams can use conditional access in a Microsoft environment to enforce location-specific policies.

Figure - zoom in


Some organizations prefer to block network traffic from specific countries completely. Still, from a threat intel point of view, I found it helpful to keep the website accessible and enforce location restrictions using conditional access. As a SOC analyst, you do not need to lose visibility against attackers running after your users' accounts.


It's normal to see many alerts for login attempts from hostile countries, but it's crucial to differentiate between login attempts using valid and invalid credentials. While both will be blocked, it's vital to highlight and prioritize alerts for login attempts with successful authentication because that means a compromised credential.


When investigating similar attempts, the first thing to do is call the account owner and get more details about login activities in the past few days. Context is very important when running an email investigation.


Conditional access can also be used with Microsoft Intune to enforce device-relevant policies. For example, you can grant or block access based on evaluating the compliance level for each device (i.e., requiring devices to run a minimum OS version, not being jail-broken or rooted, and being at or under a specific threat level)

 

Figure - zoom in


Another thing SOC analysts should monitor is new login attempts from never seen before geo-locations. If a single account has two simultaneous active sessions from two different countries, it is worth checking with the user the authenticity of the suspicious login attempt.

Like any security control, conditional access is not 100% bullet-proof, and attackers develop new ways to bypass it.
